# Cursor slash commands (this repo)

When **adding or editing** files in `.cursor/commands/`, follow all of the below.

## Required metadata block (top of file)

Start the file with this **markdown table** (same columns, same order):

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| **name** | Slash trigger, e.g. `/git-commit` |
| **id** | Stable id, kebab-case; normally equals the filename stem (no `.md`) |
| **category** | Short group label, e.g. `Git` |
| **file** | Exact filename, e.g. `git-commit.md` |
| **description** | One line: what runs, inputs/outputs implied, hard limits (e.g. no push) |

Rules:

- **name** must match what users type after `/` for this file (same as Cursor’s command name for that file).
- **file** must match the real filename on disk.
- **id** should match the filename stem unless you document a deliberate exception.

## Filename = category slug + command slug

- Pick a **category slug**: lowercase ASCII, no spaces (e.g. category `Git` → `git`).
- Pick a **command slug**: kebab-case (e.g. `commit`, `push`).
- **Filename:** `{categorySlug}-{commandSlug}.md` (example: `git-commit.md`, `git-push.md`).
- For a new category, use its slug the same way (e.g. `docs` → `docs-setup.md`).

## Body content

- After the table, use clear headings and numbered steps (same tone as existing `git-commit` / `git-push` commands).
- Cross-link related commands by **name** (e.g. `/git-push`), not only by filename.
